www.u-sub.net

40
00:02:51,433 --> 00:02:54,168
For 2 weeks, this guy makes terrifying
phone calls to the family, kidnaps

41
00:02:54,293 --> 00:02:57,642
their 8-year-old son and brutally
murders him. He deserves to die.

42
00:02:57,767 --> 00:02:59,764
Big talk is easy when you're
not the executioner.

43
00:02:59,889 --> 00:03:02,848
I'm afraid of that? Show me the switch,
I'd be happy to throw it.

44
00:03:03,016 --> 00:03:05,601
<i>It's gross that he's had 3 hots
and a cot for 17 years,</i>

45
00:03:06,418 --> 00:03:09,688
<i>but the real issue's that Jason Wilkie
randomly chose my nephew.</i>

46
00:03:09,897 --> 00:03:11,315
<i>It could have been anyone's son.</i>

47
00:03:11,483 --> 00:03:12,963
<i>Putting him to death,</i>

48
00:03:13,088 --> 00:03:16,320
<i>that's about ensuring public safety
and deterring other crimes.</i>

49
00:03:16,488 --> 00:03:18,614
<i>That was Charlie Sheridan,
uncle of the murder victim,</i>

50
00:03:18,782 --> 00:03:20,269
<i>speaking to us earlier.</i>

51
00:03:20,394 --> 00:03:22,980
<i>Jason Wilkie never confessed
to the kidnapping</i>

52
00:03:23,105 --> 00:03:26,747
<i>and gruesome murder
of 8-year-old Rex Sheridan 17 years ago.</i>

53
00:03:27,064 --> 00:03:28,833
<i>A last-minute stay of execution</i>

54
00:03:29,001 --> 00:03:30,876
<i>could only come
from the governor of Virginia.</i>

55
00:03:31,188 --> 00:03:34,357
Can't believe Lightman is in there.
Why is Lightman in there?

56
00:03:34,482 --> 00:03:37,922
It's the first case he worked on
that led to a death-penalty conviction.

57
00:03:39,178 --> 00:03:40,886
Plus there's the Zoe connection.

58
00:03:41,774 --> 00:03:44,723
<i>This just in.
Jason Wilkie was just pronounced dead,</i>

59
00:03:44,891 --> 00:03:46,600
<i>the 104th person to die by execution</i>

60
00:03:47,395 --> 00:03:50,244
<i>in the state of Virginia since 1976.</i>

61
00:03:55,940 --> 00:03:59,196
I need the case files for Wilkie trial.
The transcripts, the tapes... the lot.

62
00:03:59,573 --> 00:04:00,824
Go to city hall.

63
00:04:01,151 --> 00:04:02,782
I can't. It'll take too long.

64
00:04:02,974 --> 00:04:04,410
You kept copies. I know you did.

65
00:04:04,693 --> 00:04:06,036
You made the paper.

66
00:04:06,204 --> 00:04:07,955
Look, it's over, Cal. Please.

67
00:04:08,123 --> 00:04:09,509
For both our sakes.

68
00:04:09,918 --> 00:04:13,655
Look, I saw Wilkie lie dozens of times
during his trial,

69
00:04:14,031 --> 00:04:16,154
but last night,
he was telling the truth.

70
00:04:17,510 --> 00:04:18,613
So you're telling me,

71
00:04:18,738 --> 00:04:22,537
the woman who prosecuted Wilkie
based in large part on your science,

72
00:04:23,025 --> 00:04:24,984
- is that you got it wrong?
- No, I didn't.

73
00:04:25,109 --> 00:04:27,224
When? Last night or 17 years ago?

74
00:04:27,593 --> 00:04:28,475
Both.

75
00:04:29,562 --> 00:04:30,644
How's that possible?

76
00:04:30,812 --> 00:04:33,021
I don't know. That's what
I'm trying to figure out.

77
00:04:34,377 --> 00:04:36,400
- I didn't do it, I swear.
- Do what?

78
00:04:36,568 --> 00:04:38,295
I thought
you were fighting about me.

79
00:04:38,420 --> 00:04:39,788
No, we're not fighting.

80
00:04:39,913 --> 00:04:41,864
We were having
a work-related discussion.

81
00:04:42,032 --> 00:04:43,166
Here you are.

82
00:04:45,120 --> 00:04:47,354
So, hey, congrats
on making the paper.

83
00:04:47,763 --> 00:04:50,205
I thought teenagers
didn't read newspapers anymore.

84
00:04:50,373 --> 00:04:52,500
They do when their dad goes nuts
at an execution.

85
00:04:53,043 --> 00:04:55,085
- Don't let it go to your head.
- Ready for school?

86
00:04:55,607 --> 00:04:57,667
I forgot to tell you
I don't need a ride.

87
00:04:57,792 --> 00:04:59,745
Hannah's parents
just got her a new Prius...

88
00:04:59,870 --> 00:05:01,871
Hint, hint...
so she's picking me up.

89
00:05:06,523 --> 00:05:08,792
Look, I need those files,
so, please.

90
00:05:08,973 --> 00:05:11,361
I need you to hear something.
Now, this is the call

91
00:05:11,486 --> 00:05:14,438
that Rex Sheridan's parents
received 17 years ago

92
00:05:14,606 --> 00:05:16,190
just days before he was kidnapped.

93
00:05:16,780 --> 00:05:19,151
<i>Jack and Jill went up the hill</i>

94
00:05:19,319 --> 00:05:21,779
<i>to fetch a pail of water</i>

95
00:05:22,139 --> 00:05:24,478
<i>Jack fell down, broke his crown</i>

96
00:05:24,603 --> 00:05:27,034
<i>and Jill came tumbling after</i>

97
00:05:30,747 --> 00:05:32,580
<i>I'm gonna get you.</i>

98
00:05:33,843 --> 00:05:36,476
<i>Ready or not, here I come.</i>

99
00:05:36,601 --> 00:05:38,653
Now get this.
You know Faye and Charlie Sheridan,

100
00:05:38,778 --> 00:05:42,091
the aunt and uncle of that same
little boy that got murdered?

101
00:05:42,259 --> 00:05:45,678
Mrs. Sheridan came back home after
taking the kids to school this morning,

102
00:05:45,846 --> 00:05:48,209
found this message
on their answering machine.

103
00:05:48,334 --> 00:05:51,402
<i>Ring around the Rosie</i>

104
00:05:51,893 --> 00:05:53,519
<i>pocket full of posies</i>

105
00:05:54,702 --> 00:05:57,706
<i>ashes, ashes,</i>

106
00:05:57,831 --> 00:06:00,257
<i>we all fall down</i>

107
00:06:00,785 --> 00:06:02,361
<i>I'm gonna get you.</i>

108
00:06:03,137 --> 00:06:06,397
<i>Ready or not, here I come.</i>

109
00:06:07,553 --> 00:06:08,576
My God.

110
00:06:10,787 --> 00:06:11,989
Maybe some clown

111
00:06:12,273 --> 00:06:14,117
is just playin' silly buggers,

112
00:06:14,745 --> 00:06:16,667
after watching Wilkie
on tv all week.

113
00:06:18,146 --> 00:06:19,837
Look at the sound wave analysis.

114
00:06:20,718 --> 00:06:21,738
VOICEPRINT MATCH

115
00:06:21,863 --> 00:06:23,340
This is new FBI software.

116
00:06:23,508 --> 00:06:25,968
Each voice has features
as unique as fingerprints.

117
00:06:26,519 --> 00:06:28,095
The two callers are identical,

118
00:06:28,368 --> 00:06:29,596
17 years apart.

119
00:06:29,764 --> 00:06:30,806
This's no copycat.

120
00:06:30,974 --> 00:06:34,268
Jason Wilkie could have made
this recording before he was arrested?

121
00:06:36,127 --> 00:06:39,273
If the governor had taken my phone call,
we'd know for sure, wouldn't we?

122
00:06:39,565 --> 00:06:41,859
Doesn't it prove
it wasn't Jason Wilkie?

123
00:06:43,701 --> 00:06:45,810
Did we help execute an innocent man?

124
00:06:53,643 --> 00:06:55,069
I could do this alone

125
00:06:55,194 --> 00:06:56,290
if you'd prefer.

126
00:06:57,482 --> 00:06:59,543
You think I got the wrong
person 17 years ago.

127
00:06:59,711 --> 00:07:00,810
Don't you?

128
00:07:04,008 --> 00:07:05,799
I think you could have
made a mistake.

129
00:07:07,313 --> 00:07:08,446
So do you.

130
00:07:09,661 --> 00:07:11,885
Zoe was a young prosecutor

131
00:07:12,667 --> 00:07:14,215
eager to get a conviction,

132
00:07:14,340 --> 00:07:16,016
and you wanted to help her.

133
00:07:16,854 --> 00:07:19,878
- You still do.
- Do you charge by the hour for this?

134
00:07:20,089 --> 00:07:21,815
Classic. Deflection.

135
00:07:23,389 --> 00:07:24,826
Classic Cal Lightman.

136
00:07:25,586 --> 00:07:27,176
No, look. I saw

137
00:07:27,301 --> 00:07:30,740
- a man executed last night.
- Go on.

138
00:07:30,865 --> 00:07:33,702
I saw something on his face
I'd never seen before.

139
00:07:33,870 --> 00:07:35,432
What did you see then?

140
00:07:36,435 --> 00:07:38,332
I don't really know what it was.

141
00:07:38,720 --> 00:07:42,724
But you need to follow it to the ends of
the earth, no matter what, knowing you.

142
00:07:44,968 --> 00:07:45,978
All right.

143
00:07:46,583 --> 00:07:47,718
Come on, then.

144
00:07:53,053 --> 00:07:54,722
Have you reached your children?

145
00:07:55,050 --> 00:07:56,770
Abby and Brady are upstairs.

146
00:07:56,895 --> 00:08:00,691
Our oldest son, Oliver,
is driving back to college in Baltimore.

147
00:08:00,816 --> 00:08:03,521
We haven't been able to reach him yet,
but the FBI is waiting for him there.

148
00:08:03,646 --> 00:08:05,923
My God. Brady just turned 8.

149
00:08:06,817 --> 00:08:09,238
Rex was 8 when he was abducted.

150
00:08:10,749 --> 00:08:12,533
Vinyl, still the best?

151
00:08:12,701 --> 00:08:13,895
It's brilliant.

152
00:08:14,020 --> 00:08:15,310
It's the best.

153
00:08:15,578 --> 00:08:17,978
The heavy metal piece,
that's fantastic there.

154
00:08:21,748 --> 00:08:22,793
What are you doing?

155
00:08:24,593 --> 00:08:26,338
I thought you might have had a safe.

156
00:08:26,649 --> 00:08:28,382
That sign means a lot to us.

157
00:08:28,550 --> 00:08:29,466
Really?

158
00:08:30,162 --> 00:08:33,095
The home fed diner is the first property
my father purchased.

159
00:08:33,441 --> 00:08:34,829
No offense intended.

160
00:08:35,980 --> 00:08:37,437
So where's the tape?

161
00:08:37,562 --> 00:08:38,517
What tape?

162
00:08:38,685 --> 00:08:41,270
The one that you used to fake
the voice mail you just got,

163
00:08:41,438 --> 00:08:44,302
one from 17 years ago,
the creepy nursery rhyme tape.

164
00:08:44,427 --> 00:08:46,027
That one. Where is it?

165
00:08:46,654 --> 00:08:48,360
You think we faked that message?

166
00:08:51,462 --> 00:08:52,823
Alphabetized books.

167
00:08:53,958 --> 00:08:56,042
That's a red flag if ever I saw one.

168
00:08:57,557 --> 00:08:58,881
Wait a minute!

169
00:09:01,875 --> 00:09:03,709
You got a little quiet
all of a sudden,

170
00:09:03,877 --> 00:09:06,086
for someone
who's got such a loud mouth.

171
00:09:06,254 --> 00:09:07,713
You can't come in here and...

172
00:09:07,881 --> 00:09:09,923
That message that you claim you got,
a hoax.

173
00:09:10,091 --> 00:09:11,510
You've been on tv for years.

174
00:09:11,635 --> 00:09:14,761
You've made a career
out of getting Jason Wilkie executed.

175
00:09:14,929 --> 00:09:16,513
Now he's been done, hasn't he?

176
00:09:17,245 --> 00:09:19,600
So how are you gonna maintain
your victim status?

177
00:09:21,269 --> 00:09:22,625
What's wrong with you?

178
00:09:23,094 --> 00:09:25,189
First Wilkie did it.
Then he didn't. Now this?

179
00:09:25,721 --> 00:09:29,276
Either you enjoy inflicting emotional
pain, or you're a complete fraud.

180
00:09:34,273 --> 00:09:35,407
You're right.

181
00:09:37,384 --> 00:09:38,202
Sorry.

182
00:09:39,555 --> 00:09:41,367
I'm sorry about the books,

183
00:09:41,492 --> 00:09:45,318
but sometimes you have to use
a pickax to get at the truth,

184
00:09:45,443 --> 00:09:46,251
you know?

185
00:09:46,903 --> 00:09:49,296
You may work with the FBI,
but I want you out of my house.

186
00:09:49,652 --> 00:09:50,747
I understand

187
00:09:51,633 --> 00:09:52,633
completely.

188
00:09:52,801 --> 00:09:55,476
The FBI initially had 4 other suspects
besides Jason Wilkie...

189
00:09:55,601 --> 00:09:57,264
A school bus driver, a homeless man,

190
00:09:57,389 --> 00:09:59,944
a phone company repairman,
and a supervisor.

191
00:10:00,069 --> 00:10:02,359
They never pinpointed
the actual source of the calls.

192
00:10:02,484 --> 00:10:05,442
- Couldn't trace 'em for some reason.
- Does Lightman seem weird to you?

193
00:10:06,509 --> 00:10:08,854
He's rude, impatient, distant.

194
00:10:08,979 --> 00:10:11,655
- He seems pretty normal to me.
- Yeah, but isn't that weird?

195
00:10:11,780 --> 00:10:15,115
He may have helped execute an innocent,
and he has no emotional reaction.

196
00:10:15,240 --> 00:10:17,074
Doesn't that make him a sociopath?

197
00:10:17,242 --> 00:10:18,640
Or it's just a mask.

198
00:10:18,852 --> 00:10:21,411
Where is he? I know he's here.

199
00:10:21,579 --> 00:10:24,331
Dr. Lightman's at a meeting across town.
Can I help you, Mr. Wilkie?

200
00:10:24,499 --> 00:10:25,493
Dr. Lightman lied

201
00:10:25,618 --> 00:10:27,822
back when he said Jason
committed that crime.

202
00:10:27,947 --> 00:10:29,930
You turned Jason in
to the authorities.

203
00:10:30,055 --> 00:10:32,547
Because I thought he might be
involved somehow.

204
00:10:32,715 --> 00:10:34,532
Dr. Lightman is the one
who said he was sure.

205
00:10:34,657 --> 00:10:37,427
He's the one who convinced the jury
to put my brother on death row.

206
00:10:37,902 --> 00:10:39,805
The facts of this case
have not changed.

207
00:10:39,973 --> 00:10:42,307
The calls are happening again.
I saw it on the news.

208
00:10:42,475 --> 00:10:44,101
The real killer is still alive,

209
00:10:44,269 --> 00:10:46,186
and Jason is dead now, and...

210
00:10:49,245 --> 00:10:50,444
What have I done?

211
00:10:51,136 --> 00:10:53,034
Sir, why don't we go sit down?

212
00:10:53,159 --> 00:10:54,403
No. Listen.

213
00:10:54,571 --> 00:10:57,749
You tell Lightman
that I am suing his ass

214
00:10:57,874 --> 00:11:00,450
and the state of Virginia
in the wrongful death of my brother.

215
00:11:03,836 --> 00:11:06,613
Faye we got this whole system set up
so when your home phone rings,

216
00:11:06,738 --> 00:11:08,438
it'll ring here as well.

217
00:11:08,563 --> 00:11:10,377
Which will keep me out of your hair.

218
00:11:11,281 --> 00:11:13,213
If another call comes in,
don't panic, OK?

219
00:11:13,469 --> 00:11:15,816
Just stick with the script
that Dr. Foster's wrote out for you.

220
00:11:15,941 --> 00:11:17,491
Let's rehearse again.

221
00:11:19,972 --> 00:11:21,221
Is that him?

222
00:11:28,505 --> 00:11:29,305
Hello.

223
00:11:29,630 --> 00:11:31,971
<i>Mrs. Sheridan, it's Noah Benson.</i>

224
00:11:32,764 --> 00:11:34,109
It's my son's roommate.

225
00:11:35,277 --> 00:11:37,277
Noah, is everything all right?

226
00:11:37,402 --> 00:11:39,489
<i>An FBI agent is here
looking for Oliver.</i>

227
00:11:39,800 --> 00:11:43,050
<i>He's still not here yet, and
no one knows where he is.</i>

228
00:11:50,833 --> 00:11:54,683
So Oliver was auditioning for the men
of Fincher college calendar.

229
00:11:54,961 --> 00:11:56,502
We found a schedule on his computer.

230
00:11:56,627 --> 00:11:58,947
He had an appointment with
a photographer this afternoon,

231
00:11:59,072 --> 00:12:01,672
which may have been the last
person to have seen him.

232
00:12:01,797 --> 00:12:03,897
What aren't you telling me, Ben?

233
00:12:05,954 --> 00:12:07,885
There's people
at headquarters that don't think

234
00:12:08,010 --> 00:12:09,644
you should be involved in this case.

235
00:12:10,013 --> 00:12:12,158
Why? Because it's too personal?

236
00:12:13,386 --> 00:12:15,600
Or, because they think
I've lost my marbles?

237
00:12:16,117 --> 00:12:19,281
Or that I've already made a mistake
and got an innocent man executed?

238
00:12:19,406 --> 00:12:21,031
- They didn't say that.
- But you did.

239
00:12:21,698 --> 00:12:23,700
- Right there.
- I'm not the enemy here.

240
00:12:24,509 --> 00:12:26,009
- Really?
- Really.

241
00:12:26,619 --> 00:12:27,619
Prove it.

242
00:12:34,099 --> 00:12:37,467
Oliver Sheridan was here
for about 30 minutes.

243
00:12:38,259 --> 00:12:40,884
- Do you have any idea where he went?
- None.

244
00:12:41,329 --> 00:12:44,500
See, I was expecting
lads in varsity jackets,

245
00:12:45,344 --> 00:12:48,174
